0.body: Rust is a strong static language that brings rapid speed, memory safety and concurrency together. It's typically used in backend applications (web servers, micro services, command line applications) and is typically for system programming. In a more closer application sense, Rust is used as the main and preferred language for development in MKProjects!
0.title: Introduction

1.body: To install rust, follow the installation instructions in rustup.rs
1.title: Install

2.body: You can use any IDE you prefer, as it won't matter in the end of the day (just depends of your comfort zone) , however I do recommend compiling using Rust's command and it's compiler! (Not the RUN commands in an IDE)
2.title: IDE

3.title: Bindings and Mutability

4.body: Let's first look more into the anatomy of a simple rust program, we have the following: fn : which denotes a function main() : a main function is where code is executed by the compiler {} : the function body is where the code is put in for the function Rust's compiler can usually assume the type of a binding, such as let num = 3.0 could be a 64-bit floating-point number or f64. However, it is good practice to also let Rust know the type, and to do so, you need to know the different types that are in Rust.
4.title: Basic Types

5.body:
A scalar type represents a single value. Rust has four primary types, which are: integers (1, 2, 3), floating-point numbers (1.0, 2.1, 3.6), Boolean (true, false), and characters ('c', 'a'). To have a binding declare a type, just place a colon after it with the type: fn main(){ let int_num : i32 = 45; // 32 bit integer println!("The integer is {}!", int_num);
}
5.title: Scalar Types

6.body: An integer is a number in which has no fraction component associated with it, and can be only positive (unsigned), or positive/negative (signed) in various lengths of bits. Note: Signed integers start with i while unsigned integers start with u. On the table below you can see the variants of integers all based on their bit length. Length Signed Unsigned 8-bit i8 u8 16-bit i16 u16 32-bit i32 u32 64-bit i64 u64 128-bit i128 u128 arch isize usize
6.title: Integers

7.body:
Floating-point numbers are numbers that do have a fractional component (or decimal). In Rust, there are only a 32-bit and 64-bit variants or f32 and f64 respectively. The default is f64 and it is considered to be double precision point, while f32 is considered to be a single precision point. fn main(){ let float1 = 78.5; //By default is f64 let float2: f32 = 87.6; println!("This is f64: {}, this is f32: {}", float1, float2);
}
7.title: Floating-Point Numbers

8.body:
Rust supports the basic arithmetic that you'd probably expect to do, addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, and modulo. The code below will show an example of each: fn main(){ let sum = 6.7 + 9.8; // addition let difference = 10 - 7; // subtraction let product = 78 * 43; // multiplication let quotient = 8.0/3.0; // division let remainder = 35 % 6; // modulo
} Note: You cannot do operations between an integer and floating-point.
8.title: Operations

9.body: As like most programming languages, a Boolean type has two possible values, true and false. These values are both one byte in size and a bool type is issued with the keyword bool. fn main(){ let heads: bool = true; //explicit type annotation let tails = false; }
9.title: Boolean
